# Acknowledge Before Planning

Before thinking about or presenting any plan, **always** narrate an acknowledgement out loud first using `friday-speak.py`.

## ⚡ Zero-Delay Async Pattern — ALWAYS use this

**Fire pick-session-voice + speak acknowledgement IN THE SAME PARALLEL BATCH as your first real work tool calls.**

Do NOT make them a sequential prerequisite that blocks work from starting. Both voice calls use `block_until_ms: 0` (fire-and-forget) — they run simultaneously alongside `Read`, `Glob`, `Shell`, or any other work you start in the same message.

```
Message N (single response):
  ├── Shell: pick-session-voice.py          ← block_until_ms: 0  (no wait)
  ├── Shell: friday-speak.py "Got it…"      ← block_until_ms: 0  (no wait)
  ├── Read: the relevant file               ← starts NOW, not after speak
  └── Glob: find related files             ← starts NOW, not after speak
```

This is zero sequential overhead. The voice fires async and work starts at the same time.

## Required calls (every response, block_until_ms: 0)

```powershell
# Assign sticky voice for this chat session (no-op if already assigned)
cd d:\code\openclaw; python skill-gateway/scripts/pick-session-voice.py

# Speak acknowledgement (uses session voice automatically)
cd d:\code\openclaw; python skill-gateway/scripts/friday-speak.py "Got it. [one sentence restatement of the task]."
```

Both must have `block_until_ms: 0`. Both can be in the same message as real work tool calls — that's the point.

## Example — correct async batch

```
Tool call 1: Shell pick-session-voice.py      block_until_ms: 0
Tool call 2: Shell friday-speak.py "Got it…"  block_until_ms: 0
Tool call 3: Read d:\code\openclaw\some-file  (reads immediately, no wait)
Tool call 4: Glob **/*.py                     (searches immediately, no wait)
```

All four tool calls fire in the same message. Voice narration and actual work happen in parallel.

## Session voice persistence

`pick-session-voice.py` saves the main chat voice to `.session-voice.json` (default: `FRIDAY_TTS_VOICE` from the environment — Jarvis / Ryan). Every subsequent `friday-speak.py` in this chat uses that sticky voice for acknowledgements and status unless you opt into random main voices via `FRIDAY_TTS_MAIN_RANDOM_VOICES=true`.

**Task subagents (explore / shell / generalPurpose):** use a separate teen / young-adult voice — never the rare child persona. In **every** Shell that runs pick or speak from a subagent, prefix the session kind (PowerShell):

```powershell
cd d:\code\openclaw; $env:FRIDAY_TTS_SESSION='subagent'; python skill-gateway/scripts/pick-session-voice.py --subagent
cd d:\code\openclaw; $env:FRIDAY_TTS_SESSION='subagent'; python skill-gateway/scripts/friday-speak.py "Got it. …"
```

The parent chat keeps using the main commands above **without** `FRIDAY_TTS_SESSION` or `--subagent`.

## If you have clarifying questions

Speak the question out loud AND show it in your text reply. Still batch the voice call with any read/explore calls you can do speculatively:

```powershell
cd d:\code\openclaw; python skill-gateway/scripts/friday-speak.py "Before I proceed — [question]?"
```

## Do NOT

- Make `pick-session-voice` and `friday-speak` sequential blocking steps before work
- Silently start coding without narrating first
- Ask questions after you've already started planning
